[49m[38;5;9m- 583     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Portal integration is make-or-break for delivery.** Publishing the AVS to the patient portal requires integration with the EHR's portal APIs. Epic's MyChart, Cerner's HealtheLife, athenahealth's patient portal: each has its own integration pattern and document publishing API. You'll spend real engineering time here. Expect two to four weeks per portal integration, and more if the EHR requires certification for third-party content.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      583[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Portal integration is make-or-break for delivery.** Publishing the AVS to the patient portal requires integration with the EHR's portal APIs. Epic's MyChart, Cerner's HealtheLife, athenahealth's patient portal: each has its own integration pattern and document publishing API. You'll spend real engineering time here. Expect two to four weeks per portal integration, and more if the EHR requires certification for third-party content.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      584[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      585[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **EHR-to-pipeline connectivity matters for security posture.** For cloud EHRs, the note-signed event and FHIR pull typically cross TLS-encrypted connections to vendor public endpoints with egress controls and Secrets Manager-sourced credentials. For on-premises EHRs, plan for Direct Connect or site-to-site VPN with the FHIR gateway reachable over private IPs only. PHI in transit must never traverse the public internet unencrypted; inbound traffic to your VPC should be scoped by source IP or PrivateLink. Test the latency of this path under load: if the EHR round-trip adds 2-3 seconds, it dominates the time budget for the "summary delivered before the patient leaves" SLO.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      586[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      587[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **SMS and PHI.** SMS is not encrypted end-to-end at the carrier level. Sending clinical content (medication names, doses, warning signs, follow-up dates) via SMS constitutes PHI transmission over an unencrypted channel. Under HIPAA, this requires the patient's informed consent after disclosure of the security risks (45 CFR 164.522(b)). Most health systems enforce a content-minimization policy: SMS carries only non-PHI notifications ("Your summary is ready, view it in the portal") rather than clinical details. If your practice supports direct-to-SMS clinical content, you need documented patient consent, a content-minimization step (send only essential action items, not the full summary), and awareness of jurisdiction-specific overlays: California CMIA, Texas HB 300, and Washington's My Health My Data Act each add requirements beyond HIPAA baseline for health data transmitted via messaging. Default your pipeline to notification-plus-portal-link and require an explicit consent flag before dispatching clinical content over SMS.
